Good question! Emails from new custom domains often land in spam for several common reasons, especially when you‚Äôve just set up your email. Here‚Äôs why and how to fix it:

üõë Why Your Email Might Go to Spam

  1. New Domain Reputation:
    New domains don‚Äôt have a sending reputation yet, so spam filters are cautious.

  2. Missing or Incorrect DNS Records:
    Without proper SPF, DKIM, and DMARC records, spam filters can‚Äôt verify you‚Äôre a trusted sender.

  3. Content Triggers:
    Certain words, links, or formats in your emails can trigger spam filters.

  4. Low Engagement History:
    No previous interaction or history with recipients may make filters suspicious.

‚úÖ How to Fix It

1. Check & Set Up Proper DNS Records (Most Important!)

Make sure your domain has:

  • SPF record allowing Zoho (or your email provider) to send emails on your behalf

  • DKIM signature set up in your DNS (Zoho provides this)

  • DMARC policy (optional but recommended)

You can check your domain‚Äôs SPF/DKIM/DMARC with free tools like:

  • MXToolbox SPF Check

  • DKIM Validator

  • DMARC Analyzer

2. Warm Up Your Domain

  • Send emails to friends, colleagues first (ask them to mark as ‚ÄúNot Spam‚Äù)

  • Avoid sending mass emails immediately

  • Use clear, simple subject lines and plain text

3. Use Good Email Content

  • Avoid spammy words like ‚Äúfree,‚Äù ‚Äúurgent,‚Äù ‚Äúclick here,‚Äù ‚Äúguarantee‚Äù

  • Use professional signatures and clean formatting

  • Avoid too many links or images in early emails

4. Ask Recipients to Whitelist Your Email

Ask your contacts to add your email (support@taleemmate.com) to their address book or safe sender list.

üìß Bonus Tip: Use Zoho‚Äôs SMTP for Sending

Make sure your email client is sending emails via Zoho‚Äôs SMTP servers ‚Äî this helps with authentication.
